Here are several examples of using the echo command in Bash:

ðŸ”¹ Basic Output

echo "Hello, world!"
Prints Hello, world! to the terminal.

ðŸ”¹ Echo Variables

name="Alice"
echo "Hello, $name"
Expands and prints: Hello, Alice

ðŸ”¹ Newlines and Tabs

echo -e "Line 1\nLine 2"
echo -e "Column1\tColumn2"
-e enables interpretation of backslash escapes.

ðŸ”¹ No Trailing Newline

echo -n "No newline at end"
Prints without a trailing newline.

ðŸ”¹ Redirect Output to a File

echo "This goes to a file" > file.txt
Overwrites file.txt with the echoed text.

ðŸ”¹ Append to a File

echo "Append this line" >> file.txt
Appends the text to the end of file.txt.

ðŸ”¹ Command Substitution

echo "Today is $(date)"
Inserts the output of date into the string.

ðŸ”¹ Printing Environment Variables

echo "$HOME"
Prints the path to your home directory.

ðŸ”¹ Suppress Output

echo > /dev/null
Sends output to the voidâ€”used to discard it.
